"# Wiener's Attack on RSA: Implementation and Verification\n",
"\n",
"This notebook demonstrates Wiener's low decryption exponent attack on the RSA cryptosystem using SageMath. \n",
"\n",
"The attack is possible only if the secret exponent $\mathbf{d}$ is very small, specifically $\mathbf{d < \frac{1}{3}n^{1/4}}$. It works by exploiting the very accurate mathematical approximation $\mathbf{e/n \approx k/d}$ using continued fractions (Guaranteed by Legendre's Theorem)."
]
},
{
"cell_type": "markdown",
"id": "explanation-rand-primes",
"metadata": {},
"source": [
"## 1. Helper Function: Prime Generation\n",
"\n",
"The rand_primes function generates the two large prime factors, $p$ and $q$. For the attack to satisfy the theoretical prerequisites, these factors must be of roughly the same magnitude, satisfying the condition $\mathbf{q < p < 2q}$."
]
},
{
"cell_type": "code",
"execution_count": null,
"id": "e236fd3d-89ac-440a-8607-64fef413a706",
"metadata": {},
"outputs": [],
"source": [
"def rand_primes(size):\n",
"    """Generates random primes with q < p < 2q. Taken from https://github.com/mseckept/generalized-wiener-attack"""\n",
"    p = random_prime(1 << (size - 1), 1 << size)\n",
"    while True:\n",
"        q = random_prime(1 << (size - 1), 1 << size)\n",
"        if p < q:\n",
"            p, q = q, p\n",
"            if q < p < 2*q:\n",
"                break\n",
"    return p,q"
]
},
